  "prompt": "Business consulting SOW not complete, do we have to pay?",
  "response": "Whether you are obligated to pay for an incomplete Statement of Work (SOW) in a business consulting agreement depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Terms of the Contract**: Review the specific terms stated in the contract. Many contracts will outline payment obligations, milestones, and what constitutes completion of the work.\n\n2. **Deliverables**: If the SOW outlines specific deliverables or milestones that have not been met, you may have grounds to negotiate payment or reduce the amount owed based on incomplete work.\n\n3. **Good Faith and Fair Dealing**: Contracts usually come with an implied duty of good faith and fair dealing. If the consultant has not fulfilled their contractual obligations, you may have a case for withholding payment.\n\n4. **Negotiation**: If you believe the work is incomplete, consider discussing your concerns with the consultant. It's possible to negotiate a payment that reflects the work that has been completed.\n\n5. **Documentation**: Keep detailed records of communication and work completed. This documentation can support your position if you choose to contest a payment.\n\n6. **Legal Advice**: If the situation is complex or the amount in question is significant, consider seeking legal advice to understand your rights and obligations better.\n\nAlways consult with a legal professional for advice specific to your circumstances and to ensure that you're acting within the law and the terms of your agreement.",
